snippet.textDisplay:
A couple corrections, Mat...
- We aren't part of the community. We ARE the community.
- Youtube isn't a platform, it's a publisher with an agenda.
- They didn't move on from us; they betrayed us, the ones that made youtube, in favor of money.


Were they truly a platform, they would leave policing of "content" to other countries and not do anything (to include demonetization) save in obviously illegal/wrong cases. Who are the ones that were favored this year in the rewind? It was people with name brands that didn't show youtube in a bad light.


My suggestion is to start looking into multi-platform audiences. Youtube is committing one of the slowest suicides I've ever seen.
snippet.textOriginal:
A couple corrections, Mat...
- We aren't part of the community. We ARE the community.
- Youtube isn't a platform, it's a publisher with an agenda.

Were they truly a platform, they would leave policing of "content" to other countries and not do anything (to include demonetization) save in obviously illegal/wrong cases. Who are the ones that were favored this year in the rewind? It was people with name brands that didn't show youtube in a bad light.


My suggestion is to start looking into multi-platform audiences. Youtube is committing one of the slowest suicides I've ever seen.

"it's going to be a very different platform"
It's a publisher. In the future, they will stop being able to call themselves anything other than a publisher (or stop destroying their platform, but let's face it another website will replace YT before that happens).

"how global it is"
This is the heart of the problem right here. YouTube is no longer defined as a space for the people who post videos on YouTube. They are now looking at it as just another cable outlet that has to chase as much popularity from everyone in the world at all times.

snippet.textDisplay: You're missing another big part of it: there are no viral meme videos anymore. Events you've listed would still be just a tiny portion of rewind's runtime. Rewind back when it was loved was just a musical mishmash of memes. That flow ran dry. In 2018 they tried to replace it with a mishmash of creators, in 2019 they tried a mishmash of videos. YouTube algorithm too heavily guards the bubble of what it knows a user likes and doesn't let any random videos through. It's a platform for shows now, not for individual videos.
